g the substructure of lyric argument in groupings of poems sharing similar strategies, the author discloses the major principles that inform Horatian lyric composition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLaudatory poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 0aOdesxHistory and criticism. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 4aassimilation. 4aclassical Latin literature. 4aclassical literature. 4alinguistics. 4aliterature. 4alyric. 4apoem. 4apoems. 4apoet. 4apoetry. 4apoets. 4arhetoric. 4aspeech science. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520910300?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910300/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles